{"title_page": "The Girl King", "text_new": "{{for|the 2002 film|Girl King}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl King\n| image          = Affiche 209 La reine-gar\u00e7on Fr.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n| producer       = [[Arnie Gelbart]]<br>Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki\n| writer         = [[Michel Marc Bouchard]]\n| starring       = [[Malin Buska]]<br>[[Sarah Gadon]]<br>[[Michael Nyqvist]]<br>[[Lucas Bryant]]<br>[[Patrick Bauchau]]\n| music          = [[Anssi Tikanm\u00e4ki]]\n| cinematography = [[Guy Dufaux]]\n| editing        = [[Hans Funck]]\n| studio         = [[Marianna Films]]<br>[[Triptych Media]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2015|09|04|df=y|[[Montreal Film Festival]]}}\n| runtime        = 106 min\n| country        = Finland<br>Canada<br>Sweden<br>Germany<br>France\n| language       = English<br>French<br>German\n}}\n'''''The Girl King''''' is a 2015 biographical drama about [[Christina, Queen of Sweden]]. It was directed by [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]] and written by [[Michel Marc Bouchard]] who, after writing the screenplay for the film, wrote his stage play ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' which enjoyed a successful run in 2012 at Montreal's [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouveau Monde]] and then in English at the [[Stratford Festival]] in 2014.  The film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Carmel|title=\u2018The Girl King\u2019 premieres at the Montreal World Film Festival|url=http://www.rcinet.ca/en/2015/09/04/the-girl-king-premieres-at-the-montreal-world-film-festival/}}</ref><ref>Michel Marc Bouchard, ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' [2nd edition of the play] (Montreal, 2013). {{ISBN|9782760904309}}.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Malin Buska]] as [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Kristina]]\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Countess [[Ebba Sparre]]\n* [[Michael Nyqvist]] as Chancellor [[Axel Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Lucas Bryant]] as Count [[Johan Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Laura Birn]] as Countess Erika Erksein\n* [[Hippolyte Girardot]] as Ambassador [[Pierre Chanut|Pierre Hector Chanut]]\n* [[Peter Lohmeyer]] as Bishop Of Stockholm\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud (actor)|Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud]] as [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Karl Gustav Kasimir]]\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as [[Maria Eleonora of Brandenburg|Maria Eleonora]]\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film has received divided acclaim. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 47%, based on 15 reviews and an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/771431468/ | title=The Girl King (2015) | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes. |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> \nDana Piccoli at ''AfterEllen'' stated: \"Anytime we get to see a story about queer women in history is a good thing, and The Girl King is certainly an interesting look at this enigmatic ruler. While I wish it could have been a bit stronger in its delivery, it\u2019s still a very watchable film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/movies/453015-girl-king-tells-tale-swedens-queer-queen-christina-lady-love/ |title=\u201cThe Girl King\u201d tells the tale of Sweden\u2019s queer Queen Christina and her lady love |publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=12 December 2015|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film won two awards at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]], Best Actress to Malin Buska, and Most Popular Canadian Feature Film to director Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki. It also won best Best Film at the [[Valladolid International Film Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1254322|The Girl King}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl King, The}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Finnish drama films]]\n[[Category:Finnish LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Swedish royalty]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Christina, Queen of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 2002 film|Girl King}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl King\n| image          = Affiche 209 La reine-gar\u00e7on Fr.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n| producer       = [[Arnie Gelbart]]<br>Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki\n| writer         = [[Michel Marc Bouchard]]\n| starring       = [[Malin Buska]]<br>[[Sarah Gadon]]<br>[[Michael Nyqvist]]<br>[[Lucas Bryant]]<br>[[Patrick Bauchau]]\n| music          = [[Anssi Tikanm\u00e4ki]]\n| cinematography = [[Guy Dufaux]]\n| editing        = [[Hans Funck]]\n| studio         = [[Marianna Films]]<br>[[Triptych Media]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2015|09|04|df=y|[[Montreal Film Festival]]}}\n| runtime        = 106 min\n| country        = Finland<br>Canada<br>Sweden<br>Germany<br>France\n| language       = English<br>French<br>German\n}}\n'''''The Girl King''''' is a 2015 biographical drama about [[Christina, Queen of Sweden]]. It was directed by [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]] and written by [[Michel Marc Bouchard]] who, after writing the screenplay for the film, wrote his stage play ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' which enjoyed a successful run in 2012 at Montreal\u2019s [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouveau Monde]] and then in English at the [[Stratford Festival]] in 2014.  The film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Carmel|title=\u2018The Girl King\u2019 premieres at the Montreal World Film Festival|url=http://www.rcinet.ca/en/2015/09/04/the-girl-king-premieres-at-the-montreal-world-film-festival/}}</ref><ref>Michel Marc Bouchard, ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' [2nd edition of the play] (Montreal, 2013). {{ISBN|9782760904309}}.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Malin Buska]] as [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Kristina]]\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Countess [[Ebba Sparre]]\n* [[Michael Nyqvist]] as Chancellor [[Axel Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Lucas Bryant]] as Count [[Johan Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Laura Birn]] as Countess Erika Erksein\n* [[Hippolyte Girardot]] as Ambassador [[Pierre Chanut|Pierre Hector Chanut]]\n* [[Peter Lohmeyer]] as Bishop Of Stockholm\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud (actor)|Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud]] as [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Karl Gustav Kasimir]]\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as [[Maria Eleonora of Brandenburg|Maria Eleonora]]\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film has received divided acclaim. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 47%, based on 15 reviews and an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/771431468/ | title=The Girl King (2015) | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes. |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> \nDana Piccoli at ''AfterEllen'' stated: \"Anytime we get to see a story about queer women in history is a good thing, and The Girl King is certainly an interesting look at this enigmatic ruler. While I wish it could have been a bit stronger in its delivery, it\u2019s still a very watchable film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/movies/453015-girl-king-tells-tale-swedens-queer-queen-christina-lady-love/ |title=\u201cThe Girl King\u201d tells the tale of Sweden\u2019s queer Queen Christina and her lady love |publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=12 December 2015|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film won two awards at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]], Best Actress to Malin Buska, and Most Popular Canadian Feature Film to director Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki. It also won best Best Film at the [[Valladolid International Film Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1254322|The Girl King}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl King, The}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Finnish drama films]]\n[[Category:Finnish LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Swedish royalty]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Christina, Queen of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Girl_King"}
{"title_page": "The Death & Life of John F. Donovan", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Death & Life of John F. Donovan\n| image          = The Death and Life of John F. Donovan.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| director       = [[Xavier Dolan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nancy Grant]]\n* [[Lyse Lafontaine]]\n*Xavier Dolan\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Xavier Dolan\n* [[Jacob Tierney]]\n}}\n| story          = Xavier Dolan\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kit Harington]]\n* [[Natalie Portman]]\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]]\n* [[Susan Sarandon]]\n* [[Kathy Bates]]\n}}<!--Above the title in opening credits-->\n| narrator       = Michael Gambon\n| music          = [[Gabriel Yared]]\n| cinematography = [[Andr\u00e9 Turpin]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Xavier Dolan\n* [[Mathieu Denis]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Lyla Films\n* Sons of Manual\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Les Films S\u00e9ville]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2019|3|13|France|2019|8|23|Canada|2019|12|13|United States}}\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| runtime        = 127 minutes\n| gross          = $3.3 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Death-and-Life-of-John-F-Donovan-The-(Canada)-(2019)|website = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|title=The Death & Life of John F. Donovan at The Numbers|accessdate =November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2014021121/|website = [[Box Office Mojo]]|title=The Death & Life of John F. Donovan at Box Office Mojo|accessdate = October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Death & Life of John F. Donovan''''' is a Canadian [[drama film|drama]] film, co-written, co-produced, and directed by [[Xavier Dolan]] in his [[English language|English]]-language debut. It stars [[Kit Harington]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], [[Natalie Portman]], [[Susan Sarandon]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Thandie Newton]], [[Ben Schnetzer]], and [[Jared Keeso]]. The film deals with themes of [[celebrity]], [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid media]] in [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]], mother-son relationships, and [[homosexuality]].\n\nIt is presented as three different sequences of scenes interspersed during the film: a series set in 2017 showing a young actor who reminisces about the written correspondence he shared as a child with an American TV star who died since then, and two other series set in the mid-2000s depicting the lives of both characters at the time of the correspondence. \n\n''The Death & Life of John F. Donovan'' had its world premiere at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]], making it Dolan's first film to premiere at the festival. The film was critically panned, with many critics labeling it as \"bland\" and \"pretentious.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_death_and_life_of_john_f_donovan/|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan (2018)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=October 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2017, ''[[The Times|Times]]'' journalist Audrey Newhouse interviews actor Rupert Turner about his recently published book ''Letters to a Young Actor''. The book collects letters he received from John F. Donovan, an actor with whom he corresponded with as a child, and who died from a [[drug overdose]]. \n\nIn a flashback to the mid-2000s, Turner is a [[child actor]] who is bullied by his [[Homophobia|homophobic]] schoolmates. He idolizes Donovan, who plays the lead character in the teen drama series ''Hellsome High''. The tabloid press frequently speculates that Donovan is gay and [[closeted]]; when gossip regarding Donovan soliciting male prostitutes makes headlines, his correspondence with Turner is made public, sparking malicious speculation about the nature of Turner and Donovan's relationship. Donovan writes his final letter to Turner, and dies shortly after. \n\nIn the present, Turner says he does not know whether or not Donovan's death was related to the scandal. Newhouse muses that she initially dismissed Turner's book as \"[[First World problem|mishaps from the First World]],\" but has reconsidered based on their meeting.\n\n==Cast==\n<!-- Cast and order per opening tombstone credits, roles per closing credits scroll -->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Kit Harington]] as John F. Donovan\n* [[Natalie Portman]] as Sam Turner\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]] as Rupert Turner\n* [[Susan Sarandon]] as Grace Donovan\n* [[Kathy Bates]] as Barbara Haggermaker \n* [[Thandie Newton]] as Journalist\n* [[Ben Schnetzer]] as Rupert Turner (21 y.o.)\n* [[Amara Karan]] as Miss Kureshi\n* [[Jared Keeso]] as James Donovan\n* [[Chris Zylka]] as Will Jefford Jr.\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Liz Jones\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Amy Bosworth\n* [[Michael Gambon]] as Man in Diner\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn December 2014, it was announced that [[Kit Harington]] and [[Jessica Chastain]] would star in the film, with [[Xavier Dolan]] directing the film from a screenplay he wrote with [[Jacob Tierney]]. Harington would portray the titular character while Chastain would portray a journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/kit-harington-jessica-chastain-xavier-dolan-life-and-death-of-john-f-donovan-1201309515/|title=\u2018Game Of Thrones\u2019 Star Joins Jessica Chastain In Xavier Dolan Celebrity Satire|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Jen|last=Yamato|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> That same month, it was announced [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Kathy Bates]] had joined the cast of the film. Sarandon would portray the role of Donovan's mother, while Bates would portray the role of his manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/sarandon-bates-join-death-life-john-donovan/|title=Sarandon And Bates Join The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan|website=We Got This Covered|first=Sarah|last=Myles|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-sarandon-kathy-bates-board-755461|title=Susan Sarandon and Kathy Bates Board 'Mommy' Director's First English-Language Project (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Chris|last=O'Felt|date=December 9, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, it was announced that [[Adele]] was in talks to appear in a cameo role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/adele-hello-skyfall-in-talks-to-take-cameo-in-xavier-dolan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201618626/|title=Adele In Talks To Take Cameo In Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Ali|last=Jafaar|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> That same month, [[Michael Gambon]], [[Bella Thorne]], [[Chris Zylka]], [[Emily Hampshire]], and [[Jared Keeso]]  joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/death-life-john-f-donovan-bella-thorne-chris-zylka-michael-gambon-cast-1201643714/|title=Bella Thorne, Chris Zylka and Michael Gambon Join \u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Ramin|last=Seetoodeh|date=November 18, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016, [[Natalie Portman]], [[Nicholas Hoult]] and [[Thandie Newton]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/natalie-portman-nicholas-hoult-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201701645/|title=Natalie Portman, Nicholas Hoult Join \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, it was announced [[Ben Schnetzer]] joined the cast of the film, replacing Hoult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/xavier-dolan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-ben-schnetzer-nicholas-hoult-1201711261/|title=\n'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019: Ben Schnetzer Replaces Nicholas Hoult In Xavier Dolan\u2019s Next'|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Kate|last=Erbland|date=July 29, 2016|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref> In February 2017, it was announced [[Jacob Tremblay]] had been cast in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jacob-tremblay-star-xavier-dolans-death-life-john-f-donovan-973115|title=Jacob Tremblay to Star in Xavier Dolan's 'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan' (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=February 8, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, [[Amara Karan]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/amara-karan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-luke-tennie-vengeance-1202115957/|title=Amara Karan Joins \u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019; Luke Tennie To Star In Indie Drama \u2018Vengeance\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Gabriel Yared]] composed the film's score,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/10/05/gabriel-yared-to-score-xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan/|title=Gabriel Yared to score Xavier Dolan's 'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan'|website=Film Music Reporter|date=October 6, 2016|accessdate=October 6, 2016}}</ref> which was recorded in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/gabriel.yared.5/photos/a.1552067898338000.1073741829.1541428479401942/1975232146021571/?type=3|title=Gabriel Yared|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on July 9, 2016, in [[Montreal]].<ref name=\"filming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-xavier-dolan-competition-entry-894715|title=Cannes: Xavier Dolan on His Competition Entry and His Love of 'Home Alone'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Scott|last=Roxborough|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://daman.co.id/xavier-dolan-talks-louis-vuitton-movies-adele/|title=Xavier Dolan Talks Louis Vuitton, Movies & Adele|website=Daman|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/706263-xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-begins-filming|title=Xavier Dolan\u2019s The Death and Life of John F. Donovan Begins Filming|website=Coming Soon|first=Max|last=Evry|date=July 27, 2016|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> Principal photography on Unit 1 concluded on September 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BJ0p4Z8g6rT/|title=Off to NY for last 2 days of shooting on first unit of #deathandlifeofjohnfdonovan Gonna sleep it off for the next months after though. Happy but exhausted.|website=[[Instagram.com]]|first=Xavier|last=Dolan|date=September 1, 2016|accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>  In February 2017, production resumed in Montreal, before being completed in the spring of 2017 in [[London]] and [[Prague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/movies/xavier-dolan-still-smarting-from-scathing-reviews-of-juste-la-fin-du-monde|title=Xavier Dolan still smarting from scathing reviews of Juste la fin du monde|website=[[Montreal Gazette]]|first=Brendan|last=Kelly|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/jacob-tremblay-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201981700/|title='Room\u2019 Star Jacob Tremblay Joins Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=February 8, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nIn February 2018, Dolan confirmed via [[Instagram]] that during post-production, [[Jessica Chastain]]'s character had been cut from the film for timing and pacing reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/jessica-chastain-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-cut-xavier-dolan-1202687382/ |title=Jessica Chastain Cut From Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Fernandez |first=Matt |date=February 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-jessica-chastain-xavier-dolan-kit-harington-a8195006.html |title=Xavier Dolan explains why he cut Jessica Chastain from The Death and Life of John F. Donovan |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=February 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> In an interview in October 2018, [[Bella Thorne]] mentioned she had filmed some scenes, but they were with Chastain's character and thus were cut from the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/bella-thorne-on-her-haunted-house-and-those-paparazzi-photos.html|title=Bella Thorne on Her Haunted House and Those Paparazzi Photos|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|first=Charles|last=Bramesco|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was invited to premiere at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]] in May, but (according to artistic director [[Thierry Fremaux]]), Dolan still wasn't happy with the film, opting to continue editing.<ref name=\"Tremblay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/523726/xavier-dolan-prive-de-cannes |title=Xavier Dolan, priv\u00e9 de Cannes? |last=Tremblay |first=Odile |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2018 |work=[[Le Devoir]]}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-toronto-film-festival-world-premiere-jacob-tremblay-xavier-dolan-1202438302/|title=\u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019 World Premiere Set For Toronto|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=August 1, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan/|title = The Death and Life of John F. Donovan|website = [[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate = August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in France on March 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BtD3jXKgcF8/|title=Xavier Dolan|website=[[Instagram]]|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> It was released in Canada by Les Films S\u00e9ville on August 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2019/06/26/xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-hits-theatres-in-august/|title=Xavier Dolan's \"The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\" hits theatres in August|website=www.citynews1130.com}}</ref> It was released in the United States on December 13, 2019, by [[Momentum Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-xavier-dolan-us-release-1202189858/|title=\nXavier Dolan\u2019s Long-Delayed \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 Finally Receiving a U.S. Release|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Ryan|last=Lattanzio|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIt currently holds an approval rating of 19% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 27 reviews, with an average rating of 3.55/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"The Death and Life of John F. Donovan finds writer-director Xavier Dolan flailing at profundity with a technically assured drama that never makes sense of its own ideas.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\"/> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds an aggregated score of 28 out of 100 based on 12 critics, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2020}</ref>\n\n[[IndieWire]] dubbed the film Dolan's \"worst\" of his career; they also called the screenplay \"soapy\" and \"clumsy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/09/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-review-xavier-dolan-tiff-2018-1202002920/|title=\u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 Review: Xavier Dolan\u2019s Worst Movie Stars Kit Harington as a Depressed TV Star|last=Kohn|first=Eric|date=2018-09-11|work=IndieWire|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film one out of five stars, deeming it a \"dubious mess\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/11/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-review-xavier-dolans-wild-misfire|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan review \u2013 Xavier Dolan's wild misfire|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|date=2018-09-11|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> ''[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]]'' called the film \"mediocre at best\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff2018/review-death-and-life-john-f-donovan/|title=TIFF review: The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan|last=Ritchie|first=Kevin|date=2018-09-11|work=NOW Magazine|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-us}}</ref> [[RogerEbert.com|RogerEbert.com]] criticized Dolan's music choices and wrote that the film has \"major flaws\", but praised Tremblay's performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/festivals-and-awards/tiff-2018-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-vox-lux|title=TIFF 2018: The Death and Life of John F. Donovan, Vox Lux {{!}} Festivals & Awards {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called the cast \"impressive\", but called the film a \"half-baked, cumbersome, overlong psychodrama\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/death-life-john-f-donovan-review-1142026|title='The Death and Life of John F. Donovan': Film Review {{!}} TIFF 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a more positive review, ''[[Screen International]]'' wrote that the film \"may revisit a lot of familiar territory for Dolan but on this form it is good to welcome him home.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-toronto-review/5132549.article|title='The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan' - Toronto Review|work=Screen|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4042818}}\n\n{{Xavier Dolan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death and Life of John F. Donovan, The}}\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:Canadian coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about filmmaking]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Xavier Dolan]]\n[[Category:Gay-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Prague]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2006]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2017]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films set in Prague]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Gabriel Yared]]\n[[Category:Canadian nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Death & Life of John F. Donovan\n| image          = The Death and Life of John F. Donovan.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| director       = [[Xavier Dolan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nancy Grant]]\n* [[Lyse Lafontaine]]\n*Xavier Dolan\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Xavier Dolan\n* [[Jacob Tierney]]\n}}\n| story          = Xavier Dolan\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kit Harington]]\n* [[Natalie Portman]]\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]]\n* [[Susan Sarandon]]\n* [[Kathy Bates]]\n}}<!--Above the title in opening credits-->\n| narrator       = Michael Gambon\n| music          = [[Gabriel Yared]]\n| cinematography = [[Andr\u00e9 Turpin]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Xavier Dolan\n* [[Mathieu Denis]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Lyla Films\n* Sons of Manual\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Les Films S\u00e9ville]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2019|3|13|France|2019|8|23|Canada|2019|12|13|United States}}\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| runtime        = 127 minutes\n| gross          = $3.3 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Death-and-Life-of-John-F-Donovan-The-(Canada)-(2019)|website = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|title=The Death & Life of John F. Donovan at The Numbers|accessdate =November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2014021121/|website = [[Box Office Mojo]]|title=The Death & Life of John F. Donovan at Box Office Mojo|accessdate = October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Death & Life of John F. Donovan''''' is a Canadian [[drama film|drama]] film, co-written, co-produced, and directed by [[Xavier Dolan]] in his [[English language|English]]-language debut. It stars [[Kit Harington]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], [[Natalie Portman]], [[Susan Sarandon]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Thandie Newton]], [[Ben Schnetzer]], and [[Jared Keeso]]. The film deals with themes of [[celebrity]], [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid media]] in [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]], mother-son relationships, and [[homosexuality]].\n\nIt is presented as three different sequences of scenes interspersed during the film: a series set in 2017 showing a young actor who reminisces about the written correspondence he shared as a child with an American TV star who died since then, and two other series set in the mid-2000s depicting the lives of both characters at the time of the correspondence. \n\n''The Death & Life of John F. Donovan'' had its world premiere at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]], making it Dolan's first film to premiere at the festival. The film was critically panned, with many critics labeling it as \"bland\" and \"pretentious.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_death_and_life_of_john_f_donovan/|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan (2018)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=October 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2017, ''[[The Times|Times]]'' journalist Audrey Newhouse interviews actor Rupert Turner about his recently published book ''Letters to a Young Actor''. The book collects letters he received from John F. Donovan, an actor with whom he corresponded with as a child, and who died from a [[drug overdose]]. \n\nIn a flashback to the mid-2000s, Turner is a [[child actor]] who is bullied by his [[Homophobia|homophobic]] schoolmates. He idolizes Donovan, who plays the lead character in the teen drama series ''Hellsome High''. The tabloid press frequently speculates that Donovan is gay and [[closeted]]; when gossip regarding Donovan soliciting male prostitutes makes headlines, his correspondence with Turner is made public, sparking malicious speculation about the nature of Turner and Donovan's relationship. Donovan writes his final letter to Turner, and dies shortly after. \n\nIn the present, Turner says he does not know whether or not Donovan's death was related to the scandal. Newhouse muses that she initially dismissed Turner's book as \"[[First World problem|mishaps from the First World]],\" but has reconsidered based on their meeting.\n\n==Cast==\n<!-- Cast and order per opening tombstone credits, roles per closing credits scroll -->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Kit Harington]] as John F. Donovan\n* [[Natalie Portman]] as Sam Turner\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]] as Rupert Turner\n* [[Susan Sarandon]] as Grace Donovan\n* [[Kathy Bates]] as Barbara Haggermaker \n* [[Thandie Newton]] as Journalist\n* [[Ben Schnetzer]] as Rupert Turner (21 y.o.)\n* [[Amara Karan]] as Miss Kureshi\n* [[Jared Keeso]] as James Donovan\n* [[Chris Zylka]] as Will Jefford Jr.\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Liz Jones\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Amy Bosworth\n* [[Michael Gambon]] as Man in Diner\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn December 2014, it was announced that [[Kit Harington]] and [[Jessica Chastain]] would star in the film, with [[Xavier Dolan]] directing the film from a screenplay he wrote with [[Jacob Tierney]]. Harington would portray the titular character while Chastain would portray a journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/kit-harington-jessica-chastain-xavier-dolan-life-and-death-of-john-f-donovan-1201309515/|title=\u2018Game Of Thrones\u2019 Star Joins Jessica Chastain In Xavier Dolan Celebrity Satire|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Jen|last=Yamato|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> That same month, it was announced [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Kathy Bates]] had joined the cast of the film. Sarandon would portray the role of Donovan's mother, while Bates would portray the role of his manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/sarandon-bates-join-death-life-john-donovan/|title=Sarandon And Bates Join The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan|website=We Got This Covered|first=Sarah|last=Myles|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-sarandon-kathy-bates-board-755461|title=Susan Sarandon and Kathy Bates Board 'Mommy' Director's First English-Language Project (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Chris|last=O'Felt|date=December 9, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, it was announced that [[Adele]] was in talks to appear in a cameo role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/adele-hello-skyfall-in-talks-to-take-cameo-in-xavier-dolan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201618626/|title=Adele In Talks To Take Cameo In Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Ali|last=Jafaar|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> That same month, [[Michael Gambon]], [[Bella Thorne]], [[Chris Zylka]], [[Emily Hampshire]], and [[Jared Keeso]]  joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/death-life-john-f-donovan-bella-thorne-chris-zylka-michael-gambon-cast-1201643714/|title=Bella Thorne, Chris Zylka and Michael Gambon Join \u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Ramin|last=Seetoodeh|date=November 18, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016, [[Natalie Portman]], [[Nicholas Hoult]] and [[Thandie Newton]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/natalie-portman-nicholas-hoult-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201701645/|title=Natalie Portman, Nicholas Hoult Join \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, it was announced [[Ben Schnetzer]] joined the cast of the film, replacing Hoult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/xavier-dolan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-ben-schnetzer-nicholas-hoult-1201711261/|title=\n'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019: Ben Schnetzer Replaces Nicholas Hoult In Xavier Dolan\u2019s Next'|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Kate|last=Erbland|date=July 29, 2016|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref> In February 2017, it was announced [[Jacob Tremblay]] had been cast in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jacob-tremblay-star-xavier-dolans-death-life-john-f-donovan-973115|title=Jacob Tremblay to Star in Xavier Dolan's 'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan' (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=February 8, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, [[Amara Karan]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/amara-karan-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-luke-tennie-vengeance-1202115957/|title=Amara Karan Joins \u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019; Luke Tennie To Star In Indie Drama \u2018Vengeance\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Gabriel Yared]] composed the film's score,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/10/05/gabriel-yared-to-score-xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan/|title=Gabriel Yared to score Xavier Dolan's 'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan'|website=Film Music Reporter|date=October 6, 2016|accessdate=October 6, 2016}}</ref> which was recorded in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/gabriel.yared.5/photos/a.1552067898338000.1073741829.1541428479401942/1975232146021571/?type=3|title=Gabriel Yared|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on July 9, 2016, in [[Montreal]].<ref name=\"filming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-xavier-dolan-competition-entry-894715|title=Cannes: Xavier Dolan on His Competition Entry and His Love of 'Home Alone'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Scott|last=Roxborough|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://daman.co.id/xavier-dolan-talks-louis-vuitton-movies-adele/|title=Xavier Dolan Talks Louis Vuitton, Movies & Adele|website=Daman|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/706263-xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-begins-filming|title=Xavier Dolan\u2019s The Death and Life of John F. Donovan Begins Filming|website=Coming Soon|first=Max|last=Evry|date=July 27, 2016|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> Principal photography on Unit 1 concluded on September 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BJ0p4Z8g6rT/|title=Off to NY for last 2 days of shooting on first unit of #deathandlifeofjohnfdonovan Gonna sleep it off for the next months after though. Happy but exhausted.|website=[[Instagram.com]]|first=Xavier|last=Dolan|date=September 1, 2016|accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>  In February 2017, production resumed in Montreal, before being completed in the spring of 2017 in [[London]] and [[Prague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/movies/xavier-dolan-still-smarting-from-scathing-reviews-of-juste-la-fin-du-monde|title=Xavier Dolan still smarting from scathing reviews of Juste la fin du monde|website=[[Montreal Gazette]]|first=Brendan|last=Kelly|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/jacob-tremblay-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-1201981700/|title='Room\u2019 Star Jacob Tremblay Joins Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=February 8, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nIn February 2018, Dolan confirmed via [[Instagram]] that during post-production, [[Jessica Chastain]]'s character had been cut from the film for timing and pacing reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/jessica-chastain-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-cut-xavier-dolan-1202687382/ |title=Jessica Chastain Cut From Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Fernandez |first=Matt |date=February 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-jessica-chastain-xavier-dolan-kit-harington-a8195006.html |title=Xavier Dolan explains why he cut Jessica Chastain from The Death and Life of John F. Donovan |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=February 5, 2018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> In an interview in October 2018, [[Bella Thorne]] mentioned she had filmed some scenes, but they were with Chastain\u2019s character and thus were cut from the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/bella-thorne-on-her-haunted-house-and-those-paparazzi-photos.html|title=Bella Thorne on Her Haunted House and Those Paparazzi Photos|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|first=Charles|last=Bramesco|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was invited to premiere at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]] in May, but (according to artistic director [[Thierry Fremaux]]), Dolan still wasn't happy with the film, opting to continue editing.<ref name=\"Tremblay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/523726/xavier-dolan-prive-de-cannes |title=Xavier Dolan, priv\u00e9 de Cannes? |last=Tremblay |first=Odile |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2018 |work=[[Le Devoir]]}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-toronto-film-festival-world-premiere-jacob-tremblay-xavier-dolan-1202438302/|title=\u2018The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan\u2019 World Premiere Set For Toronto|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=August 1, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan/|title = The Death and Life of John F. Donovan|website = [[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate = August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in France on March 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BtD3jXKgcF8/|title=Xavier Dolan|website=[[Instagram]]|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> It was released in Canada by Les Films S\u00e9ville on August 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2019/06/26/xavier-dolans-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-hits-theatres-in-august/|title=Xavier Dolan's \"The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\" hits theatres in August|website=www.citynews1130.com}}</ref> It was released in the United States on December 13, 2019, by [[Momentum Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-xavier-dolan-us-release-1202189858/|title=\nXavier Dolan\u2019s Long-Delayed \u2018Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 Finally Receiving a U.S. Release|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Ryan|last=Lattanzio|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIt currently holds an approval rating of 19% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 27 reviews, with an average rating of 3.55/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"The Death and Life of John F. Donovan finds writer-director Xavier Dolan flailing at profundity with a technically assured drama that never makes sense of its own ideas.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\"/> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds an aggregated score of 28 out of 100 based on 12 critics, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2020}</ref>\n\n[[IndieWire]] dubbed the film Dolan's \"worst\" of his career; they also called the screenplay \"soapy\" and \"clumsy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/09/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-review-xavier-dolan-tiff-2018-1202002920/|title=\u2018The Death and Life of John F. Donovan\u2019 Review: Xavier Dolan\u2019s Worst Movie Stars Kit Harington as a Depressed TV Star|last=Kohn|first=Eric|date=2018-09-11|work=IndieWire|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film one out of five stars, deeming it a \"dubious mess\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/11/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-review-xavier-dolans-wild-misfire|title=The Death and Life of John F. Donovan review \u2013 Xavier Dolan's wild misfire|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|date=2018-09-11|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> ''[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]]'' called the film \"mediocre at best\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff2018/review-death-and-life-john-f-donovan/|title=TIFF review: The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan|last=Ritchie|first=Kevin|date=2018-09-11|work=NOW Magazine|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-us}}</ref> [[RogerEbert.com|RogerEbert.com]] criticized Dolan's music choices and wrote that the film has \"major flaws\", but praised Tremblay's performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/festivals-and-awards/tiff-2018-the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-vox-lux|title=TIFF 2018: The Death and Life of John F. Donovan, Vox Lux {{!}} Festivals & Awards {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called the cast \"impressive\", but called the film a \"half-baked, cumbersome, overlong psychodrama\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/death-life-john-f-donovan-review-1142026|title='The Death and Life of John F. Donovan': Film Review {{!}} TIFF 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a more positive review, ''[[Screen International]]'' wrote that the film \"may revisit a lot of familiar territory for Dolan but on this form it is good to welcome him home.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-toronto-review/5132549.article|title='The Death And Life Of John F. Donovan' - Toronto Review|work=Screen|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4042818}}\n\n{{Xavier Dolan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death and Life of John F. Donovan, The}}\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:Canadian coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about filmmaking]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Xavier Dolan]]\n[[Category:Gay-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Prague]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2006]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2017]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films set in Prague]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Gabriel Yared]]\n[[Category:Canadian nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePost-production:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Death_%26_Life_of_John_F._Donovan"}
{"title_page": "The Nun (2013 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Nun\n| image          = La Religieuse 2013 Poster.jpg\n| caption        = French theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Guillaume Nicloux]]\n| producer       = [[Sylvie Pialat]]<br/>[[Jacques-Henri Bronckart]]<br/>Olivier Bronckart\n| writer         = Guillaume Nicloux<br>[[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Beaujour]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[La Religieuse (novel)|La Religieuse]]''|[[Denis Diderot]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pauline \u00c9tienne]]\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]]\n* [[Louise Bourgoin]]\n* [[Martina Gedeck]]\n* [[Fran\u00e7oise Lebrun]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Max Richter]]\n| cinematography = [[Yves Cape]]\n| editing        = Guy Lecorne\n| distributor    = Le Pacte {{small|(France)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|2|10|Berlin|2013|3|20|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes\n| country        = France<br>Belgium<br>Germany\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \u20ac5.5 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=13422|title=La Religieuse |work=JP's Box-Office}}</ref>\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Nun''''' ({{lang-fr|'''La Religieuse'''}}) is a 2013 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Guillaume Nicloux]]. It is based on the 18th-century novel [[La Religieuse (novel)|''La Religieuse'']] by French writer [[Denis Diderot]]. The film premiered in competition at the [[63rd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlin\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_16404.html |title=Berlinale Competition 2013: Another Nine Films Confirmed  |accessdate=24 January 2013 |work=berlinale}}</ref> It received two nominations at the [[4th Magritte Awards]], winning [[Magritte Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for [[Pauline \u00c9tienne]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Lorf\u00e8vre|first=Alain|title=Trois Magritte pour \"Ernest et C\u00e9lestine\"|url=http://www.lalibre.be/culture/cinema/trois-magritte-pour-ernest-et-celestine-52ed46ea3570d7514c2f12bc|accessdate=3 February 2014|newspaper=[[La Libre Belgique]]|date=1 February 2014|language=French}}</ref> and a nomination at the [[39th C\u00e9sar Awards]].<ref name=\"C\u00e9sarNoms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/frances-cesar-awards-nominations-announced-675607 |title=Berenice Bejo, Lea Seydoux, Roman Polanski Among France's Cesar Awards Nominees |accessdate=1 February 2014 |work=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe young Suzanne Simonin is forced by her parents to become a nun. She learns that as an illegitimate child, she is expected to atone for her mother's sin. Her abbess treats her kindly, but when the abbess dies and another takes her place, Suzanne considers breaking her vows. Due to the maltreatment she undergoes, she is thrown into a world of punishment. It is not until a friend gives Suzanne some hope that she may not have to remain a nun forever that Suzanne's punishment lifts.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Pauline \u00c9tienne]] as Suzanne\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]] as Abbess Saint Eutrope\n* [[Louise Bourgoin]] as Abbess Christine\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as Suzanne's mother\n* [[Fran\u00e7oise Lebrun]] as Madame de Moni\n* [[Agathe Bonitzer]] as Sister Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* [[Alice de Lencquesaing]] as Sister Ursule\n* [[Gilles Cohen]] as Suzanne's father\n* [[Marc Barb\u00e9]] as Father Castella\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois N\u00e9gret]] as Ma\u00eetre Manouri\n* [[Nicolas Jouhet]] as clergyman Sainte Marie\n* [[Pascal Bongard]] as Archdeacon\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' {{'s}} Jordan Mintzer highlighted that director Nicloux and his co-writer Beaujour breathed new life into the classic story by making the protagonist \"much more of a fighting spirit\" and by adding a \"revised ending\". He said this film was \"held together by a terrific lead performance\".<ref>{{cite web |title =  The Nun (La Religieuse): Berlin Review|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/nun-la-religieuse-berlin-review-420082|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate = 10 February 2013}}</ref> [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']]'s Boyd van Hoeij certified the film was \"slickly assembled\" and frequently  provided a \"painting-like\" cinematography.<ref>{{cite web |title =  'The Nun' review|url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117949216/ |work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate = 10 February 2013}}</ref> ''Cine Vue'''s Patrick Gamble judged ''The Nun'' suffered from an \"inability to deviate from absurdity\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Film Festival 2013: 'The Nun' review |url =http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-nun-review.html|work = Cine Vue |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Award\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Category\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Nominee\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Result\n|-\n| [[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| Golden Berlin Bear\n| Guillaume Nicloux\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| Most Promising Actress\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Lumiere Awards]]\n| Most Promising Young Actress\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[4th Magritte Awards|Magritte Awards]]\n| [[Magritte Award for Best Foreign Film in Coproduction|Best Foreign Film in Coproduction]]\n!\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Magritte Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Isabelle Huppert on screen and stage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://medias.unifrance.org/medias/224/115/95200/presse/la-religieuse-2013-presskit-anglais-1.pdf Official Press Kit] {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://en.unifrance.org/movie/33272/the-nun#  The Nun] at UniFrance films\n* {{IMDb title|2215221|The Nun}}\n\n{{Guillaume Nicloux}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nun, The}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]