 competition at the [[63rd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlin\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_16404.html |title=Berlinale Competition 2013: Another Nine Films Confirmed  |accessdate=24 January 2013 |work=berlinale}}</ref> It received two nominations at the [[4th Magritte Awards]], winning [[Magritte Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for [[Pauline \u00c9tienne]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Lorf\u00e8vre|first=Alain|title=Trois Magritte pour \"Ernest et C\u00e9lestine\"|url=http://www.lalibre.be/culture/cinema/trois-magritte-pour-ernest-et-celestine-52ed46ea3570d7514c2f12bc|accessdate=3 February 2014|newspaper=[[La Libre Belgique]]|date=1 February 2014|language=French}}</ref> and a nomination at the [[39th C\u00e9sar Awards]].<ref name=\"C\u00e9sarNoms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/frances-cesar-awards-nominations-announced-675607 |title=Berenice Bejo, Lea Seydoux, Roman Polanski Among France's Cesar Awards Nominees |accessdate=1 February 2014 |work=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe young Suzanne Simonin is forced by her parents to become a nun. She learns that as an illegitimate child, she is expected to atone for her mother's sin. Her abbess treats her kindly, but when the abbess dies and another takes her place, Suzanne considers breaking her vows. Due to the maltreatment she undergoes, she is thrown into a world of punishment. It is not until a friend gives Suzanne some hope that she may not have to remain a nun forever that Suzanne's punishment lifts.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Pauline \u00c9tienne]] as Suzanne\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]] as Abbess Saint Eutrope\n* [[Louise Bourgoin]] as Abbess Christine\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as Suzanne's mother\n* [[Fran\u00e7oise Lebrun]] as Madame de Moni\n* [[Agathe Bonitzer]] as Sister Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* [[Alice de Lencquesaing]] as Sister Ursule\n* [[Gilles Cohen]] as Suzanne's father\n* [[Marc Barb\u00e9]] as Father Castella\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois N\u00e9gret]] as Ma\u00eetre Manouri\n* [[Nicolas Jouhet]] as clergyman Sainte Marie\n* [[Pascal Bongard]] as Archdeacon\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' {{'s}} Jordan Mintzer highlighted that director Nicloux and his co-writer Beaujour breathed new life into the classic story by making the protagonist \"much more of a fighting spirit\" and by adding a \"revised ending\". He said this film was \"held together by a terrific lead performance\".<ref>{{cite web |title =  The Nun (La Religieuse): Berlin Review|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/nun-la-religieuse-berlin-review-420082|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate = 10 February 2013}}</ref> [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']]'s Boyd van Hoeij certified the film was \"slickly assembled\" and frequently  provided a \"painting-like\" cinematography.<ref>{{cite web |title =  'The Nun' review|url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117949216/ |work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate = 10 February 2013}}</ref> ''Cine Vue'''s Patrick Gamble judged ''The Nun'' suffered from an \"inability to deviate from absurdity\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Film Festival 2013: 'The Nun' review |url =http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-nun-review.html|work = Cine Vue |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Award\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Category\n!style=\"width:250px;\"|Nominee\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Result\n|-\n| [[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| Golden Berlin Bear\n| Guillaume Nicloux\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| Most Promising Actress\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Lumiere Awards]]\n| Most Promising Young Actress\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[4th Magritte Awards|Magritte Awards]]\n| [[Magritte Award for Best Foreign Film in Coproduction|Best Foreign Film in Coproduction]]\n!\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Magritte Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Pauline Etienne \n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Isabelle Huppert on screen and stage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://medias.unifrance.org/medias/224/115/95200/presse/la-religieuse-2013-presskit-anglais-1.pdf Official Press Kit] {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://en.unifrance.org/movie/33272/the-nun#  The Nun] at UniFrance films\n* {{IMDb title|2215221|The Nun}}\n\n{{Guillaume Nicloux}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nun, The}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:Belgian drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Denis Diderot]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Max Richter]]\n[[Category:Films about Catholic nuns]]\n[[Category:Films about clerical celibacy]]\n[[Category:Films based on French novels]]\n[[Category:Films critical of the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Guillaume Nicloux]]\n[[Category:Works set in monasteries]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Nun_(2013_film)"}
{"title_page": "Rosal\u00eda de Castro", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish Galician poet, writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Rosal\u00eda de Castro\n| image        = Rosal\u00eda Castro de Murgu\u00eda por Luis Sellier.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name   = Mar\u00eda Rosal\u00eda Rita de Castro\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|df=y|1837|2|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Galicia (autonomous community)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=y|1885|7|15|1837|2|24}}\n| death_place  = [[Padr\u00f3n]], [[Galicia (autonomous community)|Galicia]], Spain\n| occupation   = [[Poet]]\n| language     = {{ubl|[[Galician language|Galician]]|[[Spanish language|Spanish]]}}\n| citizenship  = [[Spain|Spanish]]\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| period       = [[Romanticism]]\n| genre        =\n| subject      =\n| movement     = ''[[Rexurdimento]]''\n| notableworks =\n| spouse       = [[Manuel Murgu\u00eda]]\n| partner      =\n| children     =\n| relatives    =\n| influences   =\n| influenced   =\n| awards       =\n| signature    = Rosalia de Castro Firma.svg\n| website      =\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Rosal\u00eda Rita de Castro''' ({{IPA-gl|rosa\u02c8li.\u0250 \u00f0\u026a \u02c8kast\u027e\u028a}}; 24 February 1837 \u2013 15 July 1885), was a Spanish [[Romanticism|romanticist]] writer and [[poet]].\n\nWriting in Galego, the [[Galician language]], after the period known as the ''S\u00e9culos Escuros'' (lit. Dark Centuries), she became an important figure of the Galician [[Spanish Romance literature|Romantic]] movement, known today as the ''Rexurdimento'' (\"Renaissance\"), along with [[Manuel Curros Enr\u00edquez]] and [[Eduardo Pondal]]. Her poetry is marked by ''[[saudade]]'', an almost ineffable combination of nostalgia, longing and melancholy.\n\nShe married [[Manuel Murgu\u00eda]], a member of the important literary group known as the [[Real Academia Galega|Royal Galician Academy]], [[historian]], [[journalist]] and editor of Rosal\u00eda's books. The couple had seven children: Alexandra (1859\u20131937), Aura (1868\u20131942), twins Gala (1871\u20131964) and Ovidio (1871\u20131900), Amara (1873\u20131921), Adriano (1875\u20131876) and Valentina (stillborn, 1877). Only two of Rosal\u00eda's children married, Aura in 1897 and Gala in 1922; neither they nor their siblings left any children, and thus, today there are no living descendants of Rosal\u00eda de Castro and her husband. Their son Ovidio was a promising painter, his career cut short by early death.\n\nRosal\u00eda published her first collection of poetry in Galician, ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Cantares gallegos|gl}}'' (\"Galician Songs\"), on 17 May 1863. This date, 17 May, is now known as the ''[[D\u00eda das Letras Galegas]]'' (\"Galician Literature Day\"), and commemorates Rosal\u00eda's achievement by dedicating, every year, this special day to a different writer, who must also write in the Galician language, since 1963. [[D\u00eda das Letras Galegas]] is an official holiday in the Autonomous Community of Galicia.\n\nRelative poverty and sadness marked Rosal\u00eda's life, in spite of this, she had a strong sense of commitment to the poor and to the defenseless. She was a strong opponent of authoritative abuse or [[abuse of authority]] and an ardent defender of women's rights. Rosal\u00eda suffered from uterine cancer and died in Padr\u00f3n, province of A Coru\u00f1a, Spain, on 15 July 1885.\n\nShe is buried in the ''Pante\u00f3n de Galegos Ilustres'', a pantheon (mausoleum) in the [[Convent of San Domingos de Bonaval]] in Santiago de Compostela, Spain.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Rosalia de Castro Padr\u00f3n.jpg|thumb|Statue of Rosal\u00eda de Castro at [[Padr\u00f3n]].]]\n\nRosal\u00eda de Castro is today one of the unquestionable poets laureate of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]].  Highly educated, expected to speak and write in Spanish and Galician she took the bold, unconventional step of writing her early poems in the Galician language.  Her defiance earned her the contempt and spite of many that deemed Galician as a Spanish dialect fit \"only for the illiterate and the churlish\". However, Rosal\u00eda's defiant gesture won her the love and admiration of the common folk, who spoke Galician at home or on a daily basis.  Schools in Galicia,<ref>[http://escolarosaliadecastro.edu.es/ Rosalia de Castro School Association].  Vigo.</ref> in Spain,<ref>[http://www.educa.madrid.org/web/cp.rosaliadecastro.majadahonda/ Rosalia de Castro Public School].  Majadahonda (Madrid).</ref> in Russia<ref>{{YouTube|bnmk7ReCUb4|Rosalia de Castro High School no. 1558}}.  Chukotsky Proezd 6, 129327 Moscow.</ref> and in Uruguay, libraries,<ref>[http://www.vilagarcia.es/servicios/soc_cultura_biblioteca.asp Rosalia de Castro Library].  Vilagarcia de Arousa (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref> cultural associations,<ref>[http://rosaliacacheiras.org/ Rosalia de Castro Cultural Association].  Cacheiras (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|JRMATl6KeQw|Rosalia de Castro Cultural Centre}}.  Ciudad de Buenos Aires (Argentina).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|IU0Sscx-zH4|Rosalia de Castro Cultural Society}}.  Havana (Cuba).</ref> awards,<ref>[http://revistaarchivosdelsur.blogspot.com.es/2012/03/premio-rosalia-de-castro-para-maria.html Premio Rosal\u00eda de Castro para Mar\u00eda Esther V\u00e1zquez].  Revista Archivos del Sur.</ref> parks, folklore groups,<ref>{{YouTube|6EaQfp8rsVA|Agrupaci\u00f3n Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}.  Centro Gallego de Madrid.</ref><ref>{{YouTube|VKbDUVcCvf0|Agrupaci\u00f3n Folcl\u00f3rica Rosal\u00eda de Castro de Padr\u00f3n}}.</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Wv2M2pI7_i4|Cuban Grupo Folcl\u00f3rico Rosal\u00eda de Castro performing in Pobra do Carami\u00f1al}}.</ref> choirs,<ref>{{YouTube|KZ-81Ne_Hog|Coral Rosal\u00eda de Castro de Pontevedra}}.</ref><ref>[http://www.elpalmar.tv/secciones/revista/mayo/pag18.pdf Coral Rosal\u00eda de Castro de El Palmar (Murcia)].</ref> compositions of her poems,<ref name=\"Rosas_a_Rosal\u00eda\">Amancio Prada, 1998: \"[https://archive.is/20130204232838/http://en.tunesbag.com/music/Amancio+Prada/525937-rosas-a-rosalia/ Rosas a Rosal\u00eda].\"  Fonomusic.</ref><ref>Gary Bachlund, composer: \"[http://www.bachlund.org/images/Dos_Canciones_1.gif  Dos Canciones de Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"</ref> a Galician traditional morning song adorned with the lyrics of one of her poems,<ref>[http://teemix.aufeminin.com/w/musique/t4173920-various-artists-alborada-de-rosalia-de-castro-galicia-s-folklore.html Morning song \"Rosalia de Castro\" (traditional vocal)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719065538/http://teemix.aufeminin.com/w/musique/t4173920-various-artists-alborada-de-rosalia-de-castro-galicia-s-folklore.html |date=2011-07-19 }}; excerpt offered on ''Teemix\u2014Un site auFeminin.com Network''.</ref><ref>Abe R\u00e1bade, Guad\u00ed Galego and Anxo Angueira. {{YouTube|ssXDblEHILE|Morning song \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (jazz)}}; track 10 of the 2008 album \"Rosal\u00eda 21.\"</ref><ref>Carlos N\u00fa\u00f1ez, Fernanda Takai and Al\u00ea Siqueira. {{YouTube|Kae_MBI0Hac|Morning song \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (fusion)}}; track 1 of the 2009 album \"Alborada do Brasil.\"</ref> a professional sports team,<ref>[[CB Rosal\u00eda de Castro|Rosalia de Castro Basketball Team]].  Santiago de Compostela.</ref> monuments at home<ref>[http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Rosalia_de_Castro_Padr%C3%B3n.jpg Rosalia de Castro statue].  Padron (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|A9kf9KsMURw|Monument to Rosalia de Castro}}.  Alameda.  Santiago de Compostela.</ref><ref>[http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/bib_autor/rosaliadecastro/graf/fotos/14.jpg Rosalia de Castro statue].  Ferrol (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref> and abroad,<ref>[http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d4/Pr_Galiza_(Porto).jpg Monument to Rosalia de Castro].  Pra\u00e7a da Galiza.  Oporto (Portugal).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|nh03G_9xeFo|Rosalia de Castro bust}}.  Buenos Aires (Argentina).</ref><ref>[http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a3/Rosal%C3%ADa_de_Castro1.jpg Rosalia de Castro bust]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.  Parque Independencia.  Rosario (Argentina).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|cRffw3EZNS0|Rosalia de Castro bust}}.  La Rambla.  Montevideo (Uruguay).</ref> a theater,<ref>{{YouTube|biJ7AH4qBKs|Teatro Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}.  A Coru\u00f1a.</ref> restaurants,<ref>[http://mialrededor.com/36057/Vigo/360571688570/restaurante_rosalia_castro.html Restaurante Rosalia de Castro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303100846/http://mialrededor.com/36057/Vigo/360571688570/restaurante_rosalia_castro.html |date=2009-03-03 }}.  Vigo.</ref><ref>[http://www.campings-hotels.com/bar-restaurante-rosalia-de-castro_2_08_62_0.html Bar Restaurante Rosalia de Castro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708112827/http://www.campings-hotels.com/bar-restaurante-rosalia-de-castro_2_08_62_0.html |date=2011-07-08 }}.  Cornell\u00e0 de Llobregat (Barcelona).</ref><ref>[http://home.datacomm.ch/barca/pages/anfahrt.html Restaurante \"Rosalia de Castro\"].  Berne (Switzerland).</ref> a label of white wine,<ref>[http://www.lomejordegalicia.com/vinos-de-galicia/2019-albarino-rosalia-de-castro.html Rosalia de Castro Albari\u00f1o].  Sociedad Cooperativa Vitivin\u00edcola Arousana.</ref> lodgings,<ref>[http://www.booking.com/hotel/es/rosalia.html Hotel Rosalia].  Padr\u00f3n (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref><ref>[http://interhotel.com/spain/fr/hoteles/3839.html Hotel Rosalia de Castro].  Poio (Pontevedra).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|DiGRaJdUKog|Hotel Gastron\u00f3mico Casa Rosalia}}.  Os \u00c1nxeles (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref> a banknote formerly in circulation,<ref>[http://images.delcampe.com/img_large/auction/000/046/451/020_001.jpg Banknote with the portrait of Rosalia de Castro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709011034/http://images.delcampe.com/img_large/auction/000/046/451/020_001.jpg |date=2011-07-09 }}.  Delcampe International.</ref> a postage stamp,<ref>[http://sofimafilatelia.blogspot.ca/2012/04/rosalia-de-castro.html Postage stamp with the portrait of Rosalia de Castro]. Sociedad Filat\u00e9lica de Madrid.</ref> a FS98 Iberia Airbus A340,<ref>[http://cdn-www.airliners.net/aviation-photos/photos/6/6/2/0357266.jpg FS98 Iberia Airbus A340 ''Rosal\u00eda de Castro'']. Airliners. Net.</ref> a sea-rescue plane,<ref>{{YouTube|WAw0R_kBJkQ|CN-235 de Salvamento Mar\u00edtimo sobre la R\u00eda de Vigo}}.</ref> a school train<ref>{{YouTube|DvJ792eWqMI|School train Rosalia de Castro}}.</ref> and many streets<ref>[http://www.pensionpuentedelossantos.com/images/logo_02.jpg Pensi\u00f3n Residencia Puente de los Santos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207184044/http://pensionpuentedelossantos.com/images/logo_02.jpg |date=2011-02-07 }}.  Avenida de Rosal\u00eda de Castro n\u00ba 18 bis.  Ribadeo (Lugo).</ref><ref>[http://www.esculturaurbana.com/paginas/zarj003.htm Commemorative plaque to Rosalia de Castro].  Calle Rosal\u00eda de Castro.  Gij\u00f3n (Asturias).  Escultura Urbana.</ref><ref>[https://braguinha.blogs.sapo.pt/arquivo/Rosalia270.jpg Street sign in Braga (Portugal)].  Braguinha Blog.</ref> have all taken her name.\n\n==International translations==\nSmall Stations Press published Rosal\u00eda de Castro's ''Galician Songs'' in English, translated by *[[Er\u00edn Moure]], in 2013 [https://www.amazon.com/Galician-Songs-Rosal%C3%ADa-Castro/dp/9543840172]. The Moure translation of de Castro's ''New Leaves'' is expected to be published by Small Stations in September, 2016. Edwin Mellen Press also published in 2010 \"the most thorough and representative volume of poetry and prose from Rosal\u00eda de Castro (1837\u20131885) ever translated into English.\"<ref>John P. Dever and Aileen Dever: \"[http://www.mellenpress.com/mellenpress.cfm?bookid=7988&pc=9 The Poetry and Prose of Rosal\u00eda de Castro: A Bilingual Facing Page Edition].\"  Lewiston, NY: Edwin Mellen Press.  2010.</ref>  In 2007, Shearsman Books published a paperback of selected poems translated by Michael Smith.<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Michael Smith: \"[http://www.shearsman.com/pages/books/catalog/2007/castro.html Rosal\u00eda de Castro: Selected Poems] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606231645/http://www.shearsman.com/pages/books/catalog/2007/castro.html |date=2009-06-06 }}.\"  Exeter, UK: Shearsman Books.  2007.</ref>  In 2004, Louis J. Rodrigues wrote for the literary magazine ''Babel'' a translation and analysis of two Rosal\u00edan poems, ''Nas\u00edn cando as prantas nasen'' and ''Negra Sombra''.<ref>Louis J. Rodrigues, 2004: \"[http://www.benjamins.nl/cgi-bin/t_bookview.cgi?bookid=Babel%2050%3A1 Rosal\u00eda de Castro's Galician poems: ''Nas\u00edn Cand''... and ''Negra Sombra''].\"  <u>Babel</u>, '''50''', No. 1, pp. 60\u201375.</ref>  In 1991, State University of New York Press launched an English anthology edited and translated by Anna-Marie Aldaz, Barbara N. Gantt and Anne C. Bromley.<ref>Rosalia de Castro, Anna-Marie Aldaz, Barbara N. Gantt and Anne C. Bromley: \"[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Poems/Rosalia-De-Castro/e/9780791405833 Poems by Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Albany, New York: State University of New York Press.  1991.</ref>  In 1977 Kathleen Kulp-Hill translated several Galician poems as part of her work entitled \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\";<ref>Kathleen Kulp-Hill: \"[http://isbndb.com/d/publisher/twayne_publishers.html?start_item=1821 Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Boston: Twayne Publishers.  1977.</ref> this book is still available from AllBookstores.com.<ref>AllBookstores.com: \"[http://www.allbookstores.com/Castro-Rosalia-1837-1885 34 titles listed under subject: \"Castro, Rosalia De 1837\u20131885].\"</ref>  In 1964 the Spanish Ministry of Foreign Affairs published a selection of Galician poems translated into English by Charles David Ley;<ref>Rosal\u00eda de Castro and Charles David Ley: \"[http://www.smallstations.com/galician.htm Poems of Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Madrid: Ministry of Foreign Affairs.  1964.</ref> this book may be found in Spanish Rare Books libraries.<ref>[http://www.abebooks.com/librer%C3%ADa-anticuaria-jos%C3%A9-manuel-vald%C3%A9s-oviedo/7331636/sf Librer\u00eda Anticuaria \"Jos\u00e9 Manuel Vald\u00e9s\" (Oviedo, Spain)].</ref>\n\nIn Japan, the first volume of Rosal\u00edan poetry was translated in 2009 by Takekazu Asaka<ref>Professor Takekazu Asaka talks about his learning of the Galician language and his translation to Japanese of ''Cantares Gallegos''. In {{YouTube|yZDYdh61DHk|O Galego do Xap\u00f3n}}.</ref> which is available from DTP Publishing (Tokyo).  In the nineteen-nineties Katsuyo Ohata wrote two articles in the journal, \"The Review of Inquiry and Research\" at Kansai Gaidai University (Osaka, Japan) on the Galician poet: \"El inconsciente creativo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro\"<ref>Katsuyo Ohata, 1992: \"[http://www.canela.org.es/cuadernoscanela/canelapdf/cc3-4ohata.pdf El inconsciente creativo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  <u>The Review of Inquiry and Research</u>.  Kansai Gaidai University.</ref> and \"En las orillas del Sar: El mundo \u00edntimo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro.\"\n\nEditoria Cris\u00e1lida, in 2008, published an anthology of Rosal\u00eda's Galician poems in Portuguese, translated by [[Andityas Soares de Moura]].<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Andityas Soares de Moura [http://www.crisalida.com.br/site/product_info.php?cPath=27&products_id=52 \"A rosa dos claustros: poesia galega (bil\u00edngue)\"].  Belo Horizonte, Brazil: Editora Cris\u00e1lida.  2008.</ref> There is a statue in her honor in the Galicia  Square in the city of Porto, Portugal, by the sculptor Barata Feyo (September 1954).\n\nIn the French-speaking world Folle Avoine in 2003 offered a French anthology of Galician poems translated by Jose-Carlos Gonzalez.<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Jose-Carlos Gonzalez: \"[https://www.amazon.fr/dp/images/2868101550 Anthologie po\u00e9tique.  Edition bilingue fran\u00e7ais-galicien].\"  B\u00e9d\u00e9e, France: Folle Avoine.  2003.</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n[[File:1 Barata Feyo Monumento Rosalia de Castro IMG 9454.jpg|thumb|Monument to Rosal\u00eda de Castro at [[Porto, Portugal]].]]\n\nThe name Rosal\u00eda de Castro has been used by several institutions, public spaces and/or parks, and on consumer goods, thus showing the social influence and impact this poet has had on the region. Today, it is possible to find schools and universities named after the writer in the Spanish Autonomous Region of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] as well as other parts of [[Spain]]. [[Russia]], [[Venezuela]] ([[Teatro Rosal\u00eda de Castro]]) and [[Uruguay]] also have places that bear the name of this distinguished poet. Furthermore, there are numerous parks, plazas and streets, cultural associations, prizes granted to people that are intimately linked with the Galician and Spanish languages, libraries, folk groups, choirs, and even a wine with the name ''R\u00edas Baixas.'' There is also a plane from the airline [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]], as well as an aircraft belonging to the [[Maritime Safety and Rescue Society]] (''Salvamento Mar\u00edtimo),'' have been given the name of Rosal\u00eda de Castro. Moreover, there are a multitude of monuments, commemorative plaques and sculptures dedicated to her in many parts of the world.\n\nOn 23 October 1979, the last of the [[Banknotes of the Spanish peseta|500 peseta bills]] was printed, being that in 1987, this bill was to be substituted by a [[Spanish peseta|coin]] of the same value. The bill had the portrait of Rosal\u00eda de Castro displayed on the obverse side, created by Pablo Sampedro Moledo:  on the reverse side were the House/Museum of Rosal\u00eda located in Padr\u00f3n and a few handwritten verses from Rosal\u00eda de Castro's work ''Follas Novas.'' With the printing of this bill, Rosal\u00eda de Castro became, excepting [[Isabella I of Castile]], the only non-allegorical female to be placed on the obverse side of a Spanish bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bde.es/webbde/es/billemone/peseta/peseta.pdf|title=Breve historia de la Peseta (Ic\u00f3nografia)|publisher=Real Casa de la Moneda|access-date=3 December 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120412180143/http://www.bde.es/webbde/es/billemone/peseta/peseta.pdf|archivedate=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bde.es/bde/en/areas/billemone/Publico_general/Billetes_y_moned/|title=Banco de Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Banknotes and coins \u2013 General public \u2013 Peseta banknotes and coins|website=www.bde.es|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Rosal\u00eda e familia por Juan Palmeiro e fillos, A Matanza. 1883-4.jpg|thumb|225px|1884 (J. Palmeiro).<ref>{{Cite book |author=Carballo, R. |year=1981 |orig-year=1963 |pages=143\u2013234 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4GkFdFdFYagC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Historia da Literatura Galega Contempor\u00e1nea |publisher=Galaxia |isbn=84-7154-391-5|author-link=Ricardo Carballo Calero }}</ref>]]\nEach year links to its corresponding year-in-poetry article or year-in-literature article:\n\n===In Galician===\n;Poetry\n* ''Cantares gallegos'' ([[1863 in poetry|1863]])\n* ''[[Follas novas]]'' ([[1880 in poetry|1880]])\n\n;Prose\n* ''Contos da mi\u00f1a terra I'' ([[1864 in literature|1864]])\n\n===In Spanish===\n;Poetry\n* ''La Flor'' ([[1857 in poetry|1857]])\n* ''A mi madre'' ([[1863 in poetry|1863]])\n* ''En las orillas del Sar'' ([[1884 in poetry|1884]])\n\n;Prose\n[[File:Busto de Rosal\u00eda de Castro.JPG|thumb|Bust of Rosal\u00eda. Paseo de los Poetas, El Rosedal, [[Parque Tres de Febrero]], [[Buenos Aires]].]]\n* ''La hija del mar'' ([[1859 in literature|1859]])\n* ''Flavio'' ([[1861 in literature|1861]])\n* ''El cadice\u00f1o'' ([[1863 in literature|1863]])\n* ''Ruinas'' ([[1866 in literature|1866]])\n* ''Las literatas'' ([[1866 in literature|1866]])\n* ''El caballero de las botas azules'' ([[1867 in literature|1867]])\n* ''El primer loco'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n* ''El domingo de Ramos'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n* ''Padr\u00f3n y las inundaciones'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n\n==Settings in music==\n* [[Osvaldo Golijov]] set \"Lua descolorida\" in \"Three Songs for Soprano and Orchestra\" (2002)\n* [[Ant\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Abril]] set ''Cuatro canciones sobre textos gallegos'' (1957\u20131962).<ref>Fernando J. Caba\u00f1as Alam\u00e1n ''Ant\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Abril \u2013 Sonidos en Libertad'' 1993 p56</ref>\n* [[Octavio Vazquez]] set \"En Cornes\" and \"Como Chove Miudi\u00f1o\", and wrote two instrumental scenes on \"Nosa Se\u00f1ora da Barca\" and \"Eu Ben Vin Estar o Moucho\"\n* [[Adolfo Salazar]] set three poems for voice and piano in \"Tres Poemas de Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (1915)\n* {{ChoralWiki|description=Settings by various composers}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* ''Actas do Congreso Internacional de Estudios sobre Rosal\u00eda de Castro e o seu tempo'', [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2839 v.&nbsp;1], [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2840 v.&nbsp;2], [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2841 v.&nbsp;3] (1986). CCG. USC {{in lang|gl}}.\n* {{Cite book |author=Alonso Girgado, Lu\u00eds |year=1994 |title=Rosal\u00eda de Castro, rosa de sombra |publisher=Ediciones Torremozas |language=Es |isbn=84-7839-141-X }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Alvarellos, Enrique |year=1993 |url=https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/I/41g7o6KWclL.jpg |title= Mulleres destacadas de Galicia |publisher=Alvarellos Editora |pages=62\u201364 |isbn=84-85311-96-5 |language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=\u00c1lvarez Ruiz de Ojeda, V. |year=1988 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=dAf958ysWsMC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false