s Novas |publisher=Editorial Galaxia |year=1990 |isbn=84-7154-725-2|language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Historia da literatura galega |first=Franciso |last=Fern\u00e1ndez del Riego |edition=2\u00aa |year=1971 |orig-year= 1951 |publisher=Editorial Galaxia |location=Vigo |pages=95\u2013101 }}\n* {{Cite book |author-link=Xos\u00e9 Filgueira Valverde |author=Filgueira Valverde, J. |url=https://pictures.abebooks.com/LGATARI/14085336900.jpg |title=Con Rosal\u00eda de Castro en su hogar |year=1974 |publisher=Patronato Rosal\u00eda de Castro |language=gl, es}}\n* {{Cite book |author=Henri Poullain, Claude |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8jBu2cLdQ98C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Rosal\u00eda de Castro e a s\u00faa obra literaria |publisher=Galaxia |year=1989 |isbn=84-7154-687-6|language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=March, Kathleen |article=Castro, Rosal\u00eda de |title=Gran Enciclopedia Galega Silverio Ca\u00f1ada |year=2005 |isbn=84-87804-88-8 |language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Marco, Aurora |year=2007 |title=Dicionario de Mulleres Galegas |pages=99\u2013103 |publisher=A Nosa Terra |isbn=978-84-8341-146-9 |language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Mayoral, Marina |url=https://archive.org/details/lapoesiaderosali0000mayo |title=La poes\u00eda de Rosal\u00eda de Castro |publisher=Gredos |location=Madrid |language=Es |year=1974 |isbn=84-249-0571-7 |url-access=registration }}\n* {{Cite book |author-link=Manuel Murgu\u00eda |author=Murgu\u00eda, M. |title=Los Precursores |location=A Coru\u00f1a |publisher=Latorre y Mart\u00ednez editores. Imprenta de [[La Voz de Galicia]] |year=1886 |language=Es }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Pereira Bueno, Fernando |title=Rosal\u00eda de Castro: Imaxe e realidade |url=http://www.xerais.es/libro.php?id=3471695 |publisher=Xerais |year=2014 |isbn=978-84-9914-565-5 |language=Gl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Pimentel, Pascoaes, Carballo, G.-Sabell, Prado, F. de la Vega, Pi\u00f1eiro, Rof and Lorenzana |year=1952 |title=7 ensayos sobre Rosal\u00eda |publisher=Galaxia }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Rodr\u00edguez S\u00e1nchez, Francisco |title=Rosal\u00eda de Castro, estranxeira na s\u00faa patria (a persoa e a obra de onte a hoxe) |publisher=AS-PG |year=2011 |isbn=978-84-89679-99-3|language=Gl}}\n* {{Cite book |editor-last=Vilavedra |editor-first=Dolores |year=1995 |title=Diccionario da Literatura Galega |volume=I |pages=127\u2013130 |publisher=Galaxia |isbn= 84-8288-019-5|language=Gl}}\n* {{Cite book |editor-mask=6 |editor-last=Vilavedra |editor-first=Dolores |year=1997 |title=Diccionario da Literatura Galega |volume=II |publisher=Galaxia |isbn= 84-8288-137-X|language=Gl}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{OL author|3203095A}}\n* [http://rosalia.gal/ Fundaci\u00f3n Rosal\u00eda de Castro] {{in lang|gl}}.\n* [http://academia.gal/figuras-homenaxeadas/-/journal_content/56_INSTANCE_8klA/10157/23374 RAG. ''Figuras homenaxeadas''] {{in lang|gl}}.\n* [http://www.culturagalega.org/album/detalle.php?id=16&autor=Rosal%EDa%20de%20Castro ''\u00c1lbum de mulleres''] ''Consello da Cultura Galega'' {{in lang|gl}}.\n* [http://bvg.udc.es/ficha_autor.jsp?id=RosCastr&alias=Rosal%EDa+de+Castro&solapa=obras ''Biblioteca Virtual Galega'']  {{in lang|gl}}.\n* [http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/portales/rosalia_de_castro_ga/ ''Biblioteca Virtual Miguel de Cervantes'']  {{in lang|gl}}.\n* [http://bdh.bne.es/bnesearch/Search.do?text=&field1val=%22Castro%2c+Rosal%C3%ADa+de%22&field1Op=AND&numfields=1&exact=on&advanced=true&field1=autor&language=esEn ''Biblioteca Digital Hisp\u00e1nica''] ''Biblioteca Nacional de Espa\u00f1a''  {{in lang|es}}.\n* [https://wheniwasachildinferrol.neocities.org/RosaliaDeCastro/ ''Translation from Galician to English of 11 poems by Rosal\u00eda de Castro'']  {{in lang|en}}.\n* {{Librivox author |id=12179}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Galician Literature Day}}\n{{Romanticism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castro, Rosalia de}}\n[[Category:1837 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish women poets]]\n[[Category:Galician poets]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago de Compostela]]\n[[Category:Burials in Galicia]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Spain]]\n[[Category:Galician-language writers]]\n[[Category:Galician Literature Day]]\n[[Category:Galician women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Spanish poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Spanish writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish Galician poet, writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Rosal\u00eda de Castro\n| image        = Rosal\u00eda Castro de Murgu\u00eda por Luis Sellier.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| pseudonym    =\n| birth_name   = Mar\u00eda Rosal\u00eda Rita de Castro\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|df=y|1837|2|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Galicia (autonomous community)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=y|1885|7|15|1837|2|24}}\n| death_place  = [[Padr\u00f3n]], [[Galicia (autonomous community)|Galicia]], Spain\n| occupation   = [[Poet]]\n| language     = {{ubl|[[Galician language|Galician]]|[[Spanish language|Spanish]]}}\n| citizenship  = [[Spain|Spanish]]\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| period       = [[Romanticism]]\n| genre        =\n| subject      =\n| movement     = ''[[Rexurdimento]]''\n| notableworks =\n| spouse       = [[Manuel Murgu\u00eda]]\n| partner      =\n| children     =\n| relatives    =\n| influences   =\n| influenced   =\n| awards       =\n| signature    = Rosalia de Castro Firma.svg\n| website      =\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Rosal\u00eda Rita de Castro''' ({{IPA-gl|rosa\u02c8li.\u0250 \u00f0\u026a \u02c8kast\u027e\u028a}}; 24 February 1837 \u2013 15 July 1885), was a [[Galicia (Spain)|Galician]] [[Romanticism|romanticist]] writer and [[poet]].\n\nWriting in Galego, the [[Galician language]], after the period known as the ''S\u00e9culos Escuros'' (lit. Dark Centuries), she became an important figure of the Galician [[Spanish Romance literature|Romantic]] movement, known today as the ''Rexurdimento'' (\"Renaissance\"), along with [[Manuel Curros Enr\u00edquez]] and [[Eduardo Pondal]]. Her poetry is marked by ''[[saudade]]'', an almost ineffable combination of nostalgia, longing and melancholy.\n\nShe married [[Manuel Murgu\u00eda]], a member of the important literary group known as the [[Real Academia Galega|Royal Galician Academy]], [[historian]], [[journalist]] and editor of Rosal\u00eda's books. The couple had seven children: Alexandra (1859\u20131937), Aura (1868\u20131942), twins Gala (1871\u20131964) and Ovidio (1871\u20131900), Amara (1873\u20131921), Adriano (1875\u20131876) and Valentina (stillborn, 1877). Only two of Rosal\u00eda's children married, Aura in 1897 and Gala in 1922; neither they nor their siblings left any children, and thus, today there are no living descendants of Rosal\u00eda de Castro and her husband. Their son Ovidio was a promising painter, his career cut short by early death.\n\nRosal\u00eda published her first collection of poetry in Galician, ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Cantares gallegos|gl}}'' (\"Galician Songs\"), on 17 May 1863. This date, 17 May, is now known as the ''[[D\u00eda das Letras Galegas]]'' (\"Galician Literature Day\"), and commemorates Rosal\u00eda's achievement by dedicating, every year, this special day to a different writer, who must also write in the Galician language, since 1963. [[D\u00eda das Letras Galegas]] is an official holiday in the Autonomous Community of Galicia.\n\nRelative poverty and sadness marked Rosal\u00eda's life, in spite of this, she had a strong sense of commitment to the poor and to the defenseless. She was a strong opponent of authoritative abuse or [[abuse of authority]] and an ardent defender of women's rights. Rosal\u00eda suffered from uterine cancer and died in Padr\u00f3n, province of A Coru\u00f1a, Spain, on 15 July 1885.\n\nShe is buried in the ''Pante\u00f3n de Galegos Ilustres'', a pantheon (mausoleum) in the [[Convent of San Domingos de Bonaval]] in Santiago de Compostela, Spain.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Rosalia de Castro Padr\u00f3n.jpg|thumb|Statue of Rosal\u00eda de Castro at [[Padr\u00f3n]].]]\n\nRosal\u00eda de Castro is today one of the unquestionable poets laureate of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]].  Highly educated, expected to speak and write in Spanish and Galician she took the bold, unconventional step of writing her early poems in the Galician language.  Her defiance earned her the contempt and spite of many that deemed Galician as a Spanish dialect fit \"only for the illiterate and the churlish\". However, Rosal\u00eda's defiant gesture won her the love and admiration of the common folk, who spoke Galician at home or on a daily basis.  Schools in Galicia,<ref>[http://escolarosaliadecastro.edu.es/ Rosalia de Castro School Association].  Vigo.</ref> in Spain,<ref>[http://www.educa.madrid.org/web/cp.rosaliadecastro.majadahonda/ Rosalia de Castro Public School].  Majadahonda (Madrid).</ref> in Russia<ref>{{YouTube|bnmk7ReCUb4|Rosalia de Castro High School no. 1558}}.  Chukotsky Proezd 6, 129327 Moscow.</ref> and in Uruguay, libraries,<ref>[http://www.vilagarcia.es/servicios/soc_cultura_biblioteca.asp Rosalia de Castro Library].  Vilagarcia de Arousa (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref> cultural associations,<ref>[http://rosaliacacheiras.org/ Rosalia de Castro Cultural Association].  Cacheiras (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|JRMATl6KeQw|Rosalia de Castro Cultural Centre}}.  Ciudad de Buenos Aires (Argentina).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|IU0Sscx-zH4|Rosalia de Castro Cultural Society}}.  Havana (Cuba).</ref> awards,<ref>[http://revistaarchivosdelsur.blogspot.com.es/2012/03/premio-rosalia-de-castro-para-maria.html Premio Rosal\u00eda de Castro para Mar\u00eda Esther V\u00e1zquez].  Revista Archivos del Sur.</ref> parks, folklore groups,<ref>{{YouTube|6EaQfp8rsVA|Agrupaci\u00f3n Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}.  Centro Gallego de Madrid.</ref><ref>{{YouTube|VKbDUVcCvf0|Agrupaci\u00f3n Folcl\u00f3rica Rosal\u00eda de Castro de Padr\u00f3n}}.</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Wv2M2pI7_i4|Cuban Grupo Folcl\u00f3rico Rosal\u00eda de Castro performing in Pobra do Carami\u00f1al}}.</ref> choirs,<ref>{{YouTube|KZ-81Ne_Hog|Coral Rosal\u00eda de Castro de Pontevedra}}.</ref><ref>[http://www.elpalmar.tv/secciones/revista/mayo/pag18.pdf Coral Rosal\u00eda de Castro de El Palmar (Murcia)].</ref> compositions of her poems,<ref name=\"Rosas_a_Rosal\u00eda\">Amancio Prada, 1998: \"[https://archive.is/20130204232838/http://en.tunesbag.com/music/Amancio+Prada/525937-rosas-a-rosalia/ Rosas a Rosal\u00eda].\"  Fonomusic.</ref><ref>Gary Bachlund, composer: \"[http://www.bachlund.org/images/Dos_Canciones_1.gif  Dos Canciones de Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"</ref> a Galician traditional morning song adorned with the lyrics of one of her poems,<ref>[http://teemix.aufeminin.com/w/musique/t4173920-various-artists-alborada-de-rosalia-de-castro-galicia-s-folklore.html Morning song \"Rosalia de Castro\" (traditional vocal)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719065538/http://teemix.aufeminin.com/w/musique/t4173920-various-artists-alborada-de-rosalia-de-castro-galicia-s-folklore.html |date=2011-07-19 }}; excerpt offered on ''Teemix\u2014Un site auFeminin.com Network''.</ref><ref>Abe R\u00e1bade, Guad\u00ed Galego and Anxo Angueira. {{YouTube|ssXDblEHILE|Morning song \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (jazz)}}; track 10 of the 2008 album \"Rosal\u00eda 21.\"</ref><ref>Carlos N\u00fa\u00f1ez, Fernanda Takai and Al\u00ea Siqueira. {{YouTube|Kae_MBI0Hac|Morning song \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (fusion)}}; track 1 of the 2009 album \"Alborada do Brasil.\"</ref> a professional sports team,<ref>[[CB Rosal\u00eda de Castro|Rosalia de Castro Basketball Team]].  Santiago de Compostela.</ref> monuments at home<ref>[http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Rosalia_de_Castro_Padr%C3%B3n.jpg Rosalia de Castro statue].  Padron (A Coru\u00f1a).