hotel.com/spain/fr/hoteles/3839.html Hotel Rosalia de Castro].  Poio (Pontevedra).</ref><ref>{{YouTube|DiGRaJdUKog|Hotel Gastron\u00f3mico Casa Rosalia}}.  Os \u00c1nxeles (A Coru\u00f1a).</ref> a banknote formerly in circulation,<ref>[http://images.delcampe.com/img_large/auction/000/046/451/020_001.jpg Banknote with the portrait of Rosalia de Castro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709011034/http://images.delcampe.com/img_large/auction/000/046/451/020_001.jpg |date=2011-07-09 }}.  Delcampe International.</ref> a postage stamp,<ref>[http://sofimafilatelia.blogspot.ca/2012/04/rosalia-de-castro.html Postage stamp with the portrait of Rosalia de Castro]. Sociedad Filat\u00e9lica de Madrid.</ref> a FS98 Iberia Airbus A340,<ref>[http://cdn-www.airliners.net/aviation-photos/photos/6/6/2/0357266.jpg FS98 Iberia Airbus A340 ''Rosal\u00eda de Castro'']. Airliners. Net.</ref> a sea-rescue plane,<ref>{{YouTube|WAw0R_kBJkQ|CN-235 de Salvamento Mar\u00edtimo sobre la R\u00eda de Vigo}}.</ref> a school train<ref>{{YouTube|DvJ792eWqMI|School train Rosalia de Castro}}.</ref> and many streets<ref>[http://www.pensionpuentedelossantos.com/images/logo_02.jpg Pensi\u00f3n Residencia Puente de los Santos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207184044/http://pensionpuentedelossantos.com/images/logo_02.jpg |date=2011-02-07 }}.  Avenida de Rosal\u00eda de Castro n\u00ba 18 bis.  Ribadeo (Lugo).</ref><ref>[http://www.esculturaurbana.com/paginas/zarj003.htm Commemorative plaque to Rosalia de Castro].  Calle Rosal\u00eda de Castro.  Gij\u00f3n (Asturias).  Escultura Urbana.</ref><ref>[https://braguinha.blogs.sapo.pt/arquivo/Rosalia270.jpg Street sign in Braga (Portugal)].  Braguinha Blog.</ref> have all taken her name.\n\n==International translations==\nSmall Stations Press published Rosal\u00eda de Castro's ''Galician Songs'' in English, translated by *[[Er\u00edn Moure]], in 2013 [https://www.amazon.com/Galician-Songs-Rosal%C3%ADa-Castro/dp/9543840172]. The Moure translation of de Castro's ''New Leaves'' is expected to be published by Small Stations in September, 2016. Edwin Mellen Press also published in 2010 \"the most thorough and representative volume of poetry and prose from Rosal\u00eda de Castro (1837\u20131885) ever translated into English.\"<ref>John P. Dever and Aileen Dever: \"[http://www.mellenpress.com/mellenpress.cfm?bookid=7988&pc=9 The Poetry and Prose of Rosal\u00eda de Castro: A Bilingual Facing Page Edition].\"  Lewiston, NY: Edwin Mellen Press.  2010.</ref>  In 2007, Shearsman Books published a paperback of selected poems translated by Michael Smith.<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Michael Smith: \"[http://www.shearsman.com/pages/books/catalog/2007/castro.html Rosal\u00eda de Castro: Selected Poems] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606231645/http://www.shearsman.com/pages/books/catalog/2007/castro.html |date=2009-06-06 }}.\"  Exeter, UK: Shearsman Books.  2007.</ref>  In 2004, Louis J. Rodrigues wrote for the literary magazine ''Babel'' a translation and analysis of two Rosal\u00edan poems, ''Nas\u00edn cando as prantas nasen'' and ''Negra Sombra''.<ref>Louis J. Rodrigues, 2004: \"[http://www.benjamins.nl/cgi-bin/t_bookview.cgi?bookid=Babel%2050%3A1 Rosal\u00eda de Castro's Galician poems: ''Nas\u00edn Cand''... and ''Negra Sombra''].\"  <u>Babel</u>, '''50''', No. 1, pp. 60\u201375.</ref>  In 1991, State University of New York Press launched an English anthology edited and translated by Anna-Marie Aldaz, Barbara N. Gantt and Anne C. Bromley.<ref>Rosalia de Castro, Anna-Marie Aldaz, Barbara N. Gantt and Anne C. Bromley: \"[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Poems/Rosalia-De-Castro/e/9780791405833 Poems by Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Albany, New York: State University of New York Press.  1991.</ref>  In 1977 Kathleen Kulp-Hill translated several Galician poems as part of her work entitled \"Rosal\u00eda de Castro\";<ref>Kathleen Kulp-Hill: \"[http://isbndb.com/d/publisher/twayne_publishers.html?start_item=1821 Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Boston: Twayne Publishers.  1977.</ref> this book is still available from AllBookstores.com.<ref>AllBookstores.com: \"[http://www.allbookstores.com/Castro-Rosalia-1837-1885 34 titles listed under subject: \"Castro, Rosalia De 1837\u20131885].\"</ref>  In 1964 the Spanish Ministry of Foreign Affairs published a selection of Galician poems translated into English by Charles David Ley;<ref>Rosal\u00eda de Castro and Charles David Ley: \"[http://www.smallstations.com/galician.htm Poems of Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  Madrid: Ministry of Foreign Affairs.  1964.</ref> this book may be found in Spanish Rare Books libraries.<ref>[http://www.abebooks.com/librer%C3%ADa-anticuaria-jos%C3%A9-manuel-vald%C3%A9s-oviedo/7331636/sf Librer\u00eda Anticuaria \"Jos\u00e9 Manuel Vald\u00e9s\" (Oviedo, Spain)].</ref>\n\nIn Japan, the first volume of Rosal\u00edan poetry was translated in 2009 by Takekazu Asaka<ref>Professor Takekazu Asaka talks about his learning of the Galician language and his translation to Japanese of ''Cantares Gallegos''. In {{YouTube|yZDYdh61DHk|O Galego do Xap\u00f3n}}.</ref> which is available from DTP Publishing (Tokyo).  In the nineteen-nineties Katsuyo Ohata wrote two articles in the journal, \"The Review of Inquiry and Research\" at Kansai Gaidai University (Osaka, Japan) on the Galician poet: \"El inconsciente creativo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro\"<ref>Katsuyo Ohata, 1992: \"[http://www.canela.org.es/cuadernoscanela/canelapdf/cc3-4ohata.pdf El inconsciente creativo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro].\"  <u>The Review of Inquiry and Research</u>.  Kansai Gaidai University.</ref> and \"En las orillas del Sar: El mundo \u00edntimo de Rosal\u00eda de Castro.\"\n\nEditoria Cris\u00e1lida, in 2008, published an anthology of Rosal\u00eda's Galician poems in Portuguese, translated by [[Andityas Soares de Moura]].<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Andityas Soares de Moura [http://www.crisalida.com.br/site/product_info.php?cPath=27&products_id=52 \"A rosa dos claustros: poesia galega (bil\u00edngue)\"].  Belo Horizonte, Brazil: Editora Cris\u00e1lida.  2008.</ref> There is a statue in her honor in the Galicia  Square in the city of Porto, Portugal, by the sculptor Barata Feyo (September 1954).\n\nIn the French-speaking world Folle Avoine in 2003 offered a French anthology of Galician poems translated by Jose-Carlos Gonzalez.<ref>Rosalia de Castro and Jose-Carlos Gonzalez: \"[https://www.amazon.fr/dp/images/2868101550 Anthologie po\u00e9tique.  Edition bilingue fran\u00e7ais-galicien].\"  B\u00e9d\u00e9e, France: Folle Avoine.  2003.</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n[[File:1 Barata Feyo Monumento Rosalia de Castro IMG 9454.jpg|thumb|Monument to Rosal\u00eda de Castro at [[Porto, Portugal]].]]\n\nThe name Rosal\u00eda de Castro has been used by several institutions, public spaces and/or parks, and on consumer goods, thus showing the social influence and impact this poet has had on the region. Today, it is possible to find schools and universities named after the writer in the Spanish Autonomous Region of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] as well as other parts of [[Spain]]. [[Russia]], [[Venezuela]] ([[Teatro Rosal\u00eda de Castro]]) and [[Uruguay]] also have places that bear the name of this distinguished poet. Furthermore, there are numerous parks, plazas and streets, cultural associations, prizes granted to people that are intimately linked with the Galician and Spanish languages, libraries, folk groups, choirs, and even a wine with the name ''R\u00edas Baixas.'' There is also a plane from the airline [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]], as well as an aircraft belonging to the [[Maritime Safety and Rescue Society]] (''Salvamento Mar\u00edtimo),'' have been given the name of Rosal\u00eda de Castro. Moreover, there are a multitude of monuments, commemorative plaques and sculptures dedicated to her in many parts of the world.\n\nOn 23 October 1979, the last of the [[Banknotes of the Spanish peseta|500 peseta bills]] was printed, being that in 1987, this bill was to be substituted by a [[Spanish peseta|coin]] of the same value. The bill had the portrait of Rosal\u00eda de Castro displayed on the obverse side, created by Pablo Sampedro Moledo:  on the reverse side were the House/Museum of Rosal\u00eda located in Padr\u00f3n and a few handwritten verses from Rosal\u00eda de Castro's work ''Follas Novas.'' With the printing of this bill, Rosal\u00eda de Castro became, excepting [[Isabella I of Castile]], the only non-allegorical female to be placed on the obverse side of a Spanish bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bde.es/webbde/es/billemone/peseta/peseta.pdf|title=Breve historia de la Peseta (Ic\u00f3nografia)|publisher=Real Casa de la Moneda|access-date=3 December 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120412180143/http://www.bde.es/webbde/es/billemone/peseta/peseta.pdf|archivedate=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bde.es/bde/en/areas/billemone/Publico_general/Billetes_y_moned/|title=Banco de Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Banknotes and coins \u2013 General public \u2013 Peseta banknotes and coins|website=www.bde.es|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Rosal\u00eda e familia por Juan Palmeiro e fillos, A Matanza. 1883-4.jpg|thumb|225px|1884 (J. Palmeiro).<ref>{{Cite book |author=Carballo, R. |year=1981 |orig-year=1963 |pages=143\u2013234 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4GkFdFdFYagC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Historia da Literatura Galega Contempor\u00e1nea |publisher=Galaxia |isbn=84-7154-391-5|author-link=Ricardo Carballo Calero }}</ref>]]\nEach year links to its corresponding year-in-poetry article or year-in-literature article:\n\n===In Galician===\n;Poetry\n* ''Cantares gallegos'' ([[1863 in poetry|1863]])\n* ''[[Follas novas]]'' ([[1880 in poetry|1880]])\n\n;Prose\n* ''Contos da mi\u00f1a terra I'' ([[1864 in literature|1864]])\n\n===In Spanish===\n;Poetry\n* ''La Flor'' ([[1857 in poetry|1857]])\n* ''A mi madre'' ([[1863 in poetry|1863]])\n* ''En las orillas del Sar'' ([[1884 in poetry|1884]])\n\n;Prose\n[[File:Busto de Rosal\u00eda de Castro.JPG|thumb|Bust of Rosal\u00eda. Paseo de los Poetas, El Rosedal, [[Parque Tres de Febrero]], [[Buenos Aires]].]]\n* ''La hija del mar'' ([[1859 in literature|1859]])\n* ''Flavio'' ([[1861 in literature|1861]])\n* ''El cadice\u00f1o'' ([[1863 in literature|1863]])\n* ''Ruinas'' ([[1866 in literature|1866]])\n* ''Las literatas'' ([[1866 in literature|1866]])\n* ''El caballero de las botas azules'' ([[1867 in literature|1867]])\n* ''El primer loco'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n* ''El domingo de Ramos'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n* ''Padr\u00f3n y las inundaciones'' ([[1881 in literature|1881]])\n\n==Settings in music==\n* [[Osvaldo Golijov]] set \"Lua descolorida\" in \"Three Songs for Soprano and Orchestra\" (2002)\n* [[Ant\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Abril]] set ''Cuatro canciones sobre textos gallegos'' (1957\u20131962).<ref>Fernando J. Caba\u00f1as Alam\u00e1n ''Ant\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Abril \u2013 Sonidos en Libertad'' 1993 p56</ref>\n* [[Octavio Vazquez]] set \"En Cornes\" and \"Como Chove Miudi\u00f1o\", and wrote two instrumental scenes on \"Nosa Se\u00f1ora da Barca\" and \"Eu Ben Vin Estar o Moucho\"\n* [[Adolfo Salazar]] set three poems for voice and piano in \"Tres Poemas de Rosal\u00eda de Castro\" (1915)\n* {{ChoralWiki|description=Settings by various composers}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* ''Actas do Congreso Internacional de Estudios sobre Rosal\u00eda de Castro e o seu tempo'', [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2839 v.&nbsp;1], [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2840 v.&nbsp;2], [http://consellodacultura.gal/mediateca/documento.php?id=2841 v.&nbsp;3] (1986). CCG. USC {{in lang|gl}}.\n* {{Cite book |author=Alonso Girgado, Lu\u00eds |year=1994 |title=Rosal\u00eda de Castro, rosa de sombra |publisher=Edicione